<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL AIR SUSPENSION WITH TAPERED LEAF SPRINGS - AIR LINES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
        <title>AIR LINES</title>
        <para>Air is supplied to the height control valve (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) from the pressure protection valve. There are two delivery
            ports in the height control valve supplying air to the right and left air springs.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0300106" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic id="g0300106" filename="../figg03/G0300106.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                     scalefitheight="472px"/>
            <caption>Figure 6. Air Spring Hosing And Valves</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>A. LEVEL ARM BEAM</callout1>
                <callout1>B. VERTICAL LINK</callout1>
                <callout1>1. AIR LINE CONNECTING FORWARD AND REAR AIR SPRING</callout1>
                <callout1>2. LEVELING VALVE AIR SUPPLY TO RH AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                <callout1>3. LEVELING VALVE AIR SUPPLY TO LH AIR SPRINGS</callout1>
                <callout1>4. AIR INLET TO LEVELING VALVE</callout1>
                <callout1>5. PROTECTIVE HOSE WRAP</callout1>
                <callout1>6. FROM PRESSURE PROTECTION VALVE (DELIVERY TO LEVELING VALVE)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>Air lines between the front and rear axle air springs provide air flow transfer between axles to maintain
            constant frame rail height and equal load distribution between the axles, (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
        </para>
    </svcproc>
